				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Pro=
babilistic problem-solving algorithm</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be co=
nfused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_algorithm"=
 title=3D"Monte Carlo algorithm">Monte Carlo algorithm</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">

</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Approximation_d%27une_distribution_normale.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f=
f/Approximation_d%27une_distribution_normale.gif/330px-Approximation_d%27un=
e_distribution_normale.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"225"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"640" data-file-height=3D"480"=
></a><figcaption>The approximation of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distributio=
n</a> with a Monte Carlo method</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Monte Carlo methods</b>, (sometimes called <b>Monte Carlo experiments=
</b> or <b>Monte Carlo simulations</b>) are a broad class of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computation" title=3D"Computation">computational=
</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm=
">algorithms</a> that rely on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resa=
mpling_(statistics)" title=3D"Resampling (statistics)">repeated</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_sampling" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Random sampling">random sampling</a> to obtain numerical results. Th=
e underlying concept is to use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ran=
domness" title=3D"Randomness">randomness</a> to solve problems that might b=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterministic_system" title=3D"D=
eterministic system">deterministic</a> in principle. The name comes from th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_Casino" title=3D"Mon=
te Carlo Casino">Monte Carlo Casino</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Monaco" title=3D"Monaco">Monaco</a>, where the primary developer o=
f the method, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician" title=
=3D"Mathematician">mathematician</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Stanis%C5%82aw_Ulam" title=3D"Stanis=C5=82aw Ulam">Stanis=C5=82aw Ulam</=
a>, was inspired by his uncle's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
mbling" title=3D"Gambling">gambling</a> habits.
</p><p>Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classe=
s: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probabi=
lity distribution. They can also be used to model phenomena with significan=
t uncertainty in inputs, such as calculating the risk of a nuclear power pl=
ant failure. Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simul=
ations, and they can provide approximate solutions to problems that are oth=
erwise intractable or too complex to analyze mathematically.
</p><p>Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, en=
gineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics=
, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography. They have also been a=
pplied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political sci=
ence. Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important=
 and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scie=
ntific and technological breakthroughs.
</p><p>Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such =
as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curse_of_dimensionality" title=3D"Curse of dime=
nsionality">curse of dimensionality</a>, the reliability of random number g=
enerators, and the verification and validation of the results.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overview">Overview</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Overview"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods vary, but tend to follow a particular pattern:
</p>
<ol><li>Define a domain of possible inputs.</li>
<li>Generate inputs randomly from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability =
distribution</a> over the domain.</li>
<li>Perform a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterministic_algori=
thm" title=3D"Deterministic algorithm">deterministic</a> computation of the=
 outputs.</li>
<li>Aggregate the results.</li></ol>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pi_monte_carlo_all.gif" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d=
/d4/Pi_monte_carlo_all.gif/330px-Pi_monte_carlo_all.gif" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"330" height=3D"390" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
834" data-file-height=3D"986"></a><figcaption> Monte Carlo method applied t=
o approximating the value of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">=CF=80</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>For example, consider a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circula=
r_sector#Quadrant" title=3D"Circular sector">quadrant (circular sector)</a>=
 inscribed in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_square" title=
=3D"Unit square">unit square</a>. Given that the ratio of their areas is <s=
pan class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span><s=
pan class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0<=
/span>, the value of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi" title=3D"=
Pi"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span>=
</a> can be approximated using the Monte Carlo method:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-F=
OOTNOTEKalosWhitlock2008_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKalosWhitlock2008-1"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<ol><li>Draw a square, then <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inscri=
bed_figure" title=3D"Inscribed figure">inscribe</a> a quadrant within it.</=
li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_distribution_(continuo=
us)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform distribution (continuous)">Unif=
ormly</a> scatter a given number of points over the square.</li>
<li>Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance =
from the origin of less than 1.</li>
<li>The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate=
 of the ratio of the two areas, <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" =
href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0=
<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span=
><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>. Multiply the result b=
y 4 to estimate <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CF=80</span>.</li></ol>
<p>In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes=
 the quadrant. One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the=
 square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it fal=
ls within the quadrant. Aggregating the results yields our final result, th=
e approximation of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">=CF=80</span>.
</p><p>There are two important considerations:
</p>
<ol><li>If the points are not uniformly distributed, the approximation will=
 be poor.</li>
<li>The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the wh=
ole square.</li></ol>
<p>Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and=
 their use benefitted greatly from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Pseudorandom_number_generators" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudorando=
m number generators">pseudorandom number generators</a>, which are far quic=
ker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously emplo=
yed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Application">Application</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_me=
thod&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Application"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are often used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physical</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematical</a> proble=
ms and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other appr=
oaches. Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes:<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Optimization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimization">opti=
mization</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_integratio=
n" title=3D"Numerical integration">numerical integration</a>, and generatin=
g draws from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distrib=
ution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a>.
</p><p>In physics-related problems, Monte Carlo methods are useful for simu=
lating systems with many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coupling_=
(physics)" title=3D"Coupling (physics)">coupled</a> <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Degrees_of_freedom" title=3D"Degrees of freedom">degrees =
of freedom</a>, such as fluids, disordered materials, strongly coupled soli=
ds, and cellular structures (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ellular_Potts_model" title=3D"Cellular Potts model">cellular Potts model</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interacting_particle_systems" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Interacting particle systems">interacting par=
ticle systems</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McKean%E2%80%93=
Vlasov_process" title=3D"McKean=E2=80=93Vlasov process">McKean=E2=80=93Vlas=
ov processes</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinetic_theory_o=
f_gases" title=3D"Kinetic theory of gases">kinetic models of gases</a>).
</p><p>Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty" title=3D"Uncertainty">uncert=
ainty</a> in inputs such as the calculation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Risk" title=3D"Risk">risk</a> in business and, in mathematics,=
 evaluation of multidimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
tegral" title=3D"Integral">definite integrals</a> with complicated <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_conditions" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Boundary conditions">boundary conditions</a>. In application to =
systems engineering problems (space, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Oil_exploration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Oil exploration">oil exp=
loration</a>, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo=E2=80=93based predictions=
 of failure, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cost_overrun" title=
=3D"Cost overrun">cost overruns</a> and schedule overruns are routinely bet=
ter than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo=
_method#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem h=
aving a probabilistic interpretation. By the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=3D"Law of large numbers">law of larg=
e numbers</a>, integrals described by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expected value</a> of some=
 random variable can be approximated by taking the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sample_mean_and_sample_covariance" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Sample mean and sample covariance">empirical mean</a> (<abbr title=
=3D"also known as">a.k.a.</abbr> the 'sample mean') of independent samples =
of the variable. When the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabil=
ity_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distributi=
on</a> of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Markov=
 chain Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Carlo</a> (MCMC) sampler.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
nte_Carlo_method#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_no=
te-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The cen=
tral idea is to design a judicious <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Markov_chain" title=3D"Markov chain">Markov chain</a> model with a prescri=
bed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stationary_probability_distrib=
ution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stationary probability distribution">=
stationary probability distribution</a>. That is, in the limit, the samples=
 being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (targe=
t) distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ergodic_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ergodic t=
heorem">ergodic theorem</a>, the stationary distribution is approximated by=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_measure" title=3D"E=
mpirical measure">empirical measures</a> of the random states of the MCMC s=
ampler.
</p><p>In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence=
 of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation. Th=
ese flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the dis=
tributions of the random states of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Markov_process" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Markov process">Markov pr=
ocess</a> whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the=
 current random states (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McKean=
%E2%80%93Vlasov_process" title=3D"McKean=E2=80=93Vlasov process">McKean=E2=
=80=93Vlasov processes</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partic=
le_filter" title=3D"Particle filter">nonlinear filtering equation</a>).<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-kol10_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-kol10-9"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-dp13_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dp13-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other instances, a =
flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling comp=
lexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann=
=E2=80=93Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, =
and many others). These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law=
 of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dp13_=
10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Ca=
rlo_method#cite_note-dp13-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_=
note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinea=
r Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing i=
n the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by =
the sampled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_measure" tit=
le=3D"Empirical measure">empirical measures</a>. In contrast with tradition=
al Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mean-field_particle_methods" title=3D"Mean-field particle method=
s">mean-field particle</a> techniques rely on sequential interacting sample=
s. The terminology <i>mean field</i> reflects the fact that each of the <i>=
samples</i> (<abbr title=3D"also known as">a.k.a.</abbr> particles, individ=
uals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empiric=
al measures of the process. When the size of the system tends to infinity, =
these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution =
of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical=
 interaction between particles vanishes.
</p>
