<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Computational_costs">Comput=
ational costs</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Computational costs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cos=
t associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high. In gen=
eral the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which ma=
y incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a sing=
le sample is high.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sw09_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-sw09-14"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embarrassingly_parallel" title=
=3D"Embarrassingly parallel">embarrassingly parallel</a> nature of the algo=
rithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) th=
rough <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_computing" title=3D=
"Parallel computing">parallel computing</a> strategies in local processors,=
 clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cit=
e_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-16"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Ca=
rlo_method#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previo=
usly understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to=
 estimate uncertainties in the simulations. Monte Carlo simulations invert =
this approach, solving deterministic problems using <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">probabilistic</a> <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaheuristic" title=3D"Metaheuristic"=
>metaheuristics</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulated=
_annealing" title=3D"Simulated annealing">simulated annealing</a>).
</p><p>An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buffon%27s_needle_problem" title=
=3D"Buffon's needle problem">Buffon's needle problem</a>, in which <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> can be esti=
mated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips. I=
n the 1930s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enrico_Fermi" title=
=3D"Enrico Fermi">Enrico Fermi</a> first experimented with the Monte Carlo =
method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMetropolis1987_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMetr=
opolis1987-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the late 1940s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanis%C=
5%82aw_Ulam" title=3D"Stanis=C5=82aw Ulam">Stanis=C5=82aw Ulam</a> invented=
 the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was wor=
king on nuclear weapons projects at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory" title=3D"Los Alamos National Laborato=
ry">Los Alamos National Laboratory</a>. In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists=
 at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclea=
r weapon.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMetropolis1987_19-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FO=
OTNOTEMetropolis1987-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Despite having most of the necessary d=
ata, such as the average distance a neutron would travel in a substance bef=
ore it collided with an atomic nucleus and how much energy the neutron was =
likely to give off following a collision, the Los Alamos physicists were un=
able to solve the problem using conventional, deterministic mathematical me=
thods. Ulam proposed using random experiments. He recounts his inspiration =
as follows:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The first thoughts and attempts I ma=
de to practice [the Monte Carlo Method] were suggested by a question which =
occurred to me in 1946 as I was convalescing from an illness and playing so=
litaires. The question was what are the chances that a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canfield_(solitaire)" title=3D"Canfield (solitaire)">C=
anfield solitaire</a> laid out with 52 cards will come out successfully? Af=
ter spending a lot of time trying to estimate them by pure combinatorial ca=
lculations, I wondered whether a more practical method than "abstract think=
ing" might not be to lay it out say one hundred times and simply observe an=
d count the number of successful plays. This was already possible to envisa=
ge with the beginning of the new era of fast computers, and I immediately t=
hought of problems of neutron diffusion and other questions of mathematical=
 physics, and more generally how to change processes described by certain d=
ifferential equations into an equivalent form interpretable as a succession=
 of random operations. Later [in 1946], I described the idea to <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">=
John von Neumann</a>, and we began to plan actual calculations.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTEEckhardt1987_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEckhardt1987-20">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMazhdrakovBenovValkanov2018250_21-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTEMazhdrakovBenovValkanov2018250-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A colleague of von =
Neumann and Ulam, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Metropo=
lis" title=3D"Nicholas Metropolis">Nicholas Metropolis</a>, suggested using=
 the name <i>Monte Carlo</i>, which refers to the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_Casino" title=3D"Monte Carlo Casino">Monte Carl=
o Casino</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monaco" title=3D"M=
onaco">Monaco</a> where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to g=
amble.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMetropolis1987_19-2" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTN=
OTEMetropolis1987-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Monte Carlo methods were central to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Simulation" title=3D"Simulation">simulations</a> required for further=
 postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb=
, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time. Von Neuma=
nn, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Metropolis" title=3D"=
Nicholas Metropolis">Nicholas Metropolis</a> and others programmed the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ENIAC" title=3D"ENIAC">ENIAC</a> compu=
ter to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon_design#Pure_fission_we=
apons" title=3D"Nuclear weapon design">fission weapon</a> core, in the spri=
ng of 1948.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ENIAC_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-ENIAC-22"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory" title=3D"Los Alamos Nation=
al Laboratory">Los Alamos</a> for the development of the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen_bomb" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hydrog=
en bomb">hydrogen bomb</a>, and became popularized in the fields of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_chemistry" title=3D"Physic=
al chemistry">physical chemistry</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Operations_research" title=3D"Operations research">operations resea=
rch</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rand_Corporation" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rand Corporation">Rand Corporation</a> and the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Air_Force" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"U.S. Air Force">U.S. Air Force</a> were two of the major organ=
izations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Car=
lo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in m=
any different fields.
</p><p>The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carl=
o methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_McKean" title=3D"Henry McKean">Henr=
y P. McKean Jr.</a> on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parab=
olic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-mck67_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-mck67-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Car=
lo_method#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An earlier pioneering article by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Harris_(mathematician)" title=3D"Te=
d Harris (mathematician)">Theodore E. Harris</a> and Herman Kahn, published=
 in 1951, used mean-field <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_=
algorithm" title=3D"Genetic algorithm">genetic</a>-type Monte Carlo methods=
 for estimating particle transmission energies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method=
#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologie=
s are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaheuristic" title=3D"Metaheuristic">metaheu=
ristic</a>) in evolutionary computing. The origins of these mean-field comp=
utational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing" title=3D"Alan Turing">Alan =
Turing</a> on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
nte_Carlo_method#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the articles by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nils_Aall_Barricelli" title=3D"Nils Aall Barri=
celli">Nils Aall Barricelli</a> at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Institute_for_Advanced_Study" title=3D"Institute for Advanced Study">I=
nstitute for Advanced Study</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Princeton,_New_Jersey" title=3D"Princeton, New Jersey">Princeton, New Jers=
ey</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mont=
e_Carlo_method#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_Monte_Carlo" title=
=3D"Quantum Monte Carlo">Quantum Monte Carlo</a>, and more specifically <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffusion_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Diffu=
sion Monte Carlo">diffusion Monte Carlo methods</a> can also be interpreted=
 as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Feynman" title=3D"Richard Feynman">Feynman</a>=
=E2=80=93<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Kac" title=3D"Mark K=
ac">Kac</a> path integrals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dp04_29-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dp=
04-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dmm002_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dmm002-30=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dmm00m_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dmm00m-31"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dm-esaim03_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dm-esaim03-3=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-caffarel1_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-caffarel1-=
33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-caffarel2_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-caffarel2=
-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-h84_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-h84-35"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to =
Enrico Fermi and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_D._Richtmy=
er" title=3D"Robert D. Richtmyer">Robert Richtmyer</a> who developed in 194=
8 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but the first heuristic-lik=
e and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a. Resampled or Reconfiguration =
Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum system=
s (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H. Hetherington in 1984.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-h84_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-h84-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In molecular chem=
istry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pru=
ning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal=
 work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marshall_Rosenbluth" titl=
e=3D"Marshall Rosenbluth">Marshall N. Rosenbluth</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arianna_W._Rosenbluth" title=3D"Arianna W. Rosenblut=
h">Arianna W. Rosenbluth</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_37-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-:0=
-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>The use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_Monte=
_Carlo_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sequential Monte Carlo method=
">sequential Monte Carlo</a> in advanced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D"Signal processing">signal processing</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"=
Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference</a> is more recent. It was in 1993, =
that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_me=
thod#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the first application of a Monte Carlo <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Resam=
pling (statistics)">resampling</a> algorithm in Bayesian statistical infere=
nce. The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstr=
ated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm do=
es not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the sy=
stem. Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on =
a related "Monte Carlo filter",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-39"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and the ones by Pierre Del Moral<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dm9622_40-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_m=
ethod#cite_note-dm9622-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Mo=
ral, Andr=C3=A9 Monin and G=C3=A9rard Salut<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cit=
e_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> on particle filters published in the mid-1990s. Part=
icle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989=E2=80=931992 =
by P. Del Moral, J. C. Noyer, G. Rigal, and G. Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a =
series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Te=
chnique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and th=
e <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www.laas.fr/p=
ublic/en">LAAS-CNRS</a> (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Sy=
stems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Ca=
rlo_method#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-=
43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_metho=
d#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-47"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an =
acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechani=
sm.
</p><p>From 1950 to 1996, all the publications on sequential Monte Carlo me=
thodologies, including the pruning and resample Monte Carlo methods introdu=
ced in computational physics and molecular chemistry, present natural and h=
euristic-like algorithms applied to different situations without a single p=
roof of their consistency, nor a discussion on the bias of the estimates an=
d on genealogical and ancestral tree based algorithms. The mathematical fou=
ndations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were =
written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dm9622_40-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#=
cite_note-dm9622-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:22_48-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_not=
e-:22-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes =
were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines a=
nd Terry Lyons,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:42_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-:42-49"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_C=
arlo_method#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral a=
nd Terry Lyons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:52_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-:52-52"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P=
. Del Moral, A. Guionnet and L. Miclo.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dmm002_30-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method=
#cite_note-dmm002-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dg99_53-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_n=
ote-dg99-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dg01_54-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dg01-=
54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definitions">Definitions</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_me=
thod&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Definitions=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>There is no consensus on how <i>Monte Carlo</i> should be defined. For e=
xample, Ripley<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ripley_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-Ripley-55"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> defines most probabilistic modeling as <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_simulation" title=3D"Stochastic simulation">s=
tochastic simulation</a></i>, with <i>Monte Carlo</i> being reserved for <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_integration" title=3D"Mo=
nte Carlo integration">Monte Carlo integration</a> and Monte Carlo statisti=
cal tests. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shlomo_Sawilowsky" titl=
e=3D"Shlomo Sawilowsky">Sawilowsky</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sawilowsky_56-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_me=
thod#cite_note-Sawilowsky-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> distinguishes between a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation" title=3D"Simulation">simulati=
on</a>, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is=
 a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a techniqu=
e that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem, and a Mo=
nte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical prope=
rties of some phenomenon (or behavior).
</p><p>Here are some examples:
</p>
<ul><li>Simulation: Drawing <i>one</i> pseudo-random uniform variable from =
the interval [0,1] can be used to simulate the tossing of a coin: If the va=
lue is less than or equal to 0.50 designate the outcome as heads, but if th=
e value is greater than 0.50 designate the outcome as tails. This is a simu=
lation, but not a Monte Carlo simulation.</li>
<li>Monte Carlo method: Pouring out a box of coins on a table, and then com=
puting the ratio of coins that land heads versus tails is a Monte Carlo met=
hod of determining the behavior of repeated coin tosses, but it is not a si=
mulation.</li>
<li>Monte Carlo simulation: Drawing <i>a large number</i> of pseudo-random =
uniform variables from the interval [0,1] at one time, or once at many diff=
erent times, and assigning values less than or equal to 0.50 as heads and g=
reater than 0.50 as tails, is a <i>Monte Carlo simulation</i> of the behavi=
or of repeatedly tossing a coin.</li></ul>
<p>Kalos and Whitlock<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kalos_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-Kalos-5=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> point out that such distinctions are not always easy to main=
tain. For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stocha=
stic process. It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be =
described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte=
 Carlo methods. "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneousl=
y as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sa=
mpling."
</p><p>Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gelman-Rubin_statistic" title=3D"Gel=
man-Rubin statistic">Gelman-Rubin statistic</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Monte_Carlo_and_random_numb=
ers">Monte Carlo and random numbers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
11" title=3D"Edit section: Monte Carlo and random numbers"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based =
on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis. The Monte Carlo simul=
ation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results o=
f these experiments are not well known.
Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown paramet=
ers, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-usaus_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-usaus-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Monte Carlo simulation =
methods do not always require <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rand=
om_number_generation#True_vs._pseudo-random_numbers" title=3D"Random number=
 generation">truly random numbers</a> to be useful (although, for some appl=
ications such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primality_testing=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Primality testing">primality testing</a>, =
unpredictability is vital).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-59"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Pseudora=
ndom number generator">pseudorandom</a> sequences, making it easy to test a=
nd re-run simulations. The only quality usually necessary to make good <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation" title=3D"Simulation">simul=
ations</a> is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a=
 certain sense.
</p><p>What this means depends on the application, but typically they shoul=
d pass a series of statistical tests. Testing that the numbers are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_distribution_(continuous)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Uniform distribution (continuous)">uniformly dist=
ributed</a> or follow another desired distribution when a large enough numb=
er of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and mo=
st common ones. Weak correlations between successive samples are also often=
 desirable/necessary.
</p><p>Sawilowsky lists the characteristics of a high-quality Monte Carlo s=
imulation:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sawilowsky_56-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-Sawilowsky-5=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>the (pseudo-random) number generator has certain characteristics (e=
.g. a long "period" before the sequence repeats)</li>
<li>the (pseudo-random) number generator produces values that pass tests fo=
r randomness</li>
<li>there are enough samples to ensure accurate results</li>
<li>the proper sampling technique is used</li>
<li>the algorithm used is valid for what is being modeled</li>
<li>it simulates the phenomenon in question.</li></ul>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-random_number_sampling" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudo-random number sampling">Pseudo-random=
 number sampling</a> algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed=
 pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a giv=
en <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=
=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-discrepancy_sequences" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Low-discrepancy sequences">Low-discrepancy s=
equences</a> are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they=
 ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than =
Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences. Methods bas=
ed on their use are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-M=
onte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Quasi-Monte Carlo method">quasi-Monte Carlo met=
hods</a>.
</p><p>In an effort to assess the impact of random number quality on Monte =
Carlo simulation outcomes, astrophysical researchers tested cryptographical=
ly secure pseudorandom numbers generated via Intel's <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/RDRAND" title=3D"RDRAND">RDRAND</a> instruction set, as =
compared to those derived from algorithms, like the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_Twister" title=3D"Mersenne Twister">Mersenne Twi=
ster</a>, in Monte Carlo simulations of radio flares from <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brown_dwarfs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Brown =
dwarfs">brown dwarfs</a>. No statistically significant difference was found=
 between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and R=
DRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 10<sup>7</sup> random numb=
ers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Monte_Carlo_simulation_vers=
us_&quot;what_if&quot;_scenarios"><span id=3D"Monte_Carlo_simulation_versus=
_.22what_if.22_scenarios"></span>Monte Carlo simulation versus "what if" sc=
enarios</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMont=
e_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: M=
onte Carlo simulation versus &quot;what if&quot; scenarios"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carl=
o simulations =E2=80=93 for example, deterministic modeling using single-po=
int estimates. Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best g=
uess" estimate. Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for ea=
ch input variable are chosen and the results recorded.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-F=
OOTNOTEVose200813_61-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVose200813-61"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability dist=
ribution">probability distribution</a> for each variable to produce hundred=
s or thousands of possible outcomes. The results are analyzed to get probab=
ilities of different outcomes occurring.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVose200=
816_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mont=
e_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVose200816-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, a =
comparison of a spreadsheet cost construction model run using traditional "=
what if" scenarios, and then running the comparison again with Monte Carlo =
simulation and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangular_distribu=
tion" title=3D"Triangular distribution">triangular probability distribution=
s</a> shows that the Monte Carlo analysis has a narrower range than the "wh=
at if" analysis.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left=
:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ikipedia:AUDIENCE" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wikipedia:AUDIENCE"><span=
 title=3D"An editor has requested that an example be provided. (May 2012)">=
example needed</span></a></i>]</sup> This is because the "what if" analysis=
 gives equal weight to all scenarios (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Corporate_finance#Quantifying_uncertainty" title=3D"Corporate finan=
ce">quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance</a>), while the Monte Carl=
o method hardly samples in the very low probability regions. The samples in=
 such regions are called "rare events".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_=
method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Applicati=
ons"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with =
significant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty" title=3D"=
Uncertainty">uncertainty</a> in inputs and systems with many <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coupling_(physics)" title=3D"Coupling (physics)"=
>coupled</a> degrees of freedom. Areas of application include:
</p>
