<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method_in_st=
atistical_physics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Monte Carlo method in sta=
tistical physics">Monte Carlo method in statistical physics</a></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are very important in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Computational_physics" title=3D"Computational physics">computati=
onal physics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_chemist=
ry" title=3D"Physical chemistry">physical chemistry</a>, and related applie=
d fields, and have diverse applications from complicated <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_chromodynamics" title=3D"Quantum chromodynam=
ics">quantum chromodynamics</a> calculations to designing <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_shield" title=3D"Heat shield">heat shields</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerodynamics" title=3D"Aerody=
namics">aerodynamic</a> forms as well as in modeling radiation transport fo=
r radiation dosimetry calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-6=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_physics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statis=
tical physics">statistical physics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Monte_Carlo_molecular_modeling" title=3D"Monte Carlo molecular modeli=
ng">Monte Carlo molecular modeling</a> is an alternative to computational <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_dynamics" title=3D"Molecu=
lar dynamics">molecular dynamics</a>, and Monte Carlo methods are used to c=
ompute <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_field_theory" t=
itle=3D"Statistical field theory">statistical field theories</a> of simple =
particle and polymer systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_37-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-:0=
-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Quantum =
Monte Carlo">Quantum Monte Carlo</a> methods solve the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Many-body_problem" title=3D"Many-body problem">many-bo=
dy problem</a> for quantum systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-kol10_9-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite=
_note-kol10-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dp13_10-2" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dp13=
-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-dp04_29-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-dp04-29"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiation_material_sci=
ence" title=3D"Radiation material science">radiation materials science</a>,=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_collision_approximatio=
n" title=3D"Binary collision approximation">binary collision approximation<=
/a> for simulating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_implantatio=
n" title=3D"Ion implantation">ion implantation</a> is usually based on a Mo=
nte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_=
method#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In experimental <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Particle_physics" title=3D"Particle physics">particle physic=
s</a>, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Particle_detector" title=3D"Particle detector">detectors</a=
>, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory. =
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrophysics" title=3D"Astrophy=
sics">astrophysics</a>, they are used in such diverse manners as to model b=
oth <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galaxy" title=3D"Galaxy">galax=
y</a> evolution<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and m=
icrowave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Monte Carlo methods are als=
o used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ensemble_forecasting=
" title=3D"Ensemble forecasting">ensemble models</a> that form the basis of=
 modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_weather_predicti=
on" title=3D"Numerical weather prediction">weather forecasting</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Engineering">Engineering</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_me=
thod&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Engineering=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensitivity_analysis" title=3D"Sensitivity analysis=
">sensitivity analysis</a> and quantitative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Probabilistic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Probabilistic">prob=
abilistic</a> analysis in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_=
design_(chemical_engineering)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Process desig=
n (chemical engineering)">process design</a>. The need arises from the inte=
ractive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations. =
For example,
</p>
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microelectronics" title=
=3D"Microelectronics">microelectronics engineering</a>, Monte Carlo methods=
 are applied to analyze correlated and uncorrelated variations in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analog_signal" title=3D"Analog signal">an=
alog</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_data" title=
=3D"Digital data">digital</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inte=
grated_circuits" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integrated circuits">integr=
ated circuits</a>.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geostatistics" title=3D"Geo=
statistics">geostatistics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Geometallurgy" title=3D"Geometallurgy">geometallurgy</a>, Monte Carlo metho=
ds underpin the design of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mineral_=
processing" title=3D"Mineral processing">mineral processing</a> <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_flow_diagram" title=3D"Process flow d=
iagram">flowsheets</a> and contribute to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Quantitative_risk_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantitat=
ive risk analysis">quantitative risk analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTEMazhdrakovBenovValkanov2018250_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMazhdrakovBe=
novValkanov2018250-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"Fl=
uid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>, in particular <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gas_dynamics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gas dynamics">ra=
refied gas dynamics</a>, where the Boltzmann equation is solved for finite =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knudsen_number" title=3D"Knudsen n=
umber">Knudsen number</a> fluid flows using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Direct_simulation_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Direct simulation Mon=
te Carlo">direct simulation Monte Carlo</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cit=
e_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> method in combination with highly efficient computat=
ional algorithms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li=
>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomous_robotics" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Autonomous robotics">autonomous robotics</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_localization" title=3D"Mo=
nte Carlo localization">Monte Carlo localization</a> can determine the posi=
tion of a robot. It is often applied to stochastic filters such as the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalman_filter" title=3D"Kalman filter"=
>Kalman filter</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_fil=
ter" title=3D"Particle filter">particle filter</a> that forms the heart of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simultaneous_localization_and_=
mapping" title=3D"Simultaneous localization and mapping">SLAM</a> (simultan=
eous localization and mapping) algorithm.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telecommunications" title=
=3D"Telecommunications">telecommunications</a>, when planning a wireless ne=
twork, the design must be proven to work for a wide variety of scenarios th=
at depend mainly on the number of users, their locations and the services t=
hey want to use. Monte Carlo methods are typically used to generate these u=
sers and their states. The network performance is then evaluated and, if re=
sults are not satisfactory, the network design goes through an optimization=
 process.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reliability_engineering" ti=
tle=3D"Reliability engineering">reliability engineering</a>, Monte Carlo si=
mulation is used to compute system-level response given the component-level=
 response.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D=
"Signal processing">signal processing</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"Bayesian inference">Bayesian infer=
ence</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_filter" title=
=3D"Particle filter">particle filters</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sequential_Monte_Carlo_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"S=
equential Monte Carlo method">sequential Monte Carlo techniques</a> are a c=
lass of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean-field_particle_method=
s" title=3D"Mean-field particle methods">mean-field particle methods</a> fo=
r sampling and computing the posterior distribution of a signal process giv=
en some noisy and partial observations using interacting <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_measure" title=3D"Empirical measure">empir=
ical measures</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-72"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></l=
i></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Climate_change_and_radiativ=
e_forcing">Climate change and radiative forcing</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Climate change and radiative forcing=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPCC" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"IPCC">Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change</a> relies on Mon=
te Carlo methods in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_de=
nsity_function" title=3D"Probability density function">probability density =
function</a> analysis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiative=
_forcing" title=3D"Radiative forcing">radiative forcing</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte=
_Carlo_method#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_biology">Comp=
utational biology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit =
section: Computational biology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_biology" title=3D"Computational biology">c=
omputational biology</a>, for example for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bayesian_inference_in_phylogeny" title=3D"Bayesian inference in phy=
logeny">Bayesian inference in phylogeny</a>, or for studying biological sys=
tems such as genomes, proteins,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOjedaGarciaLondo=
noChen2009_74-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOjedaGarciaLondonoChen2009-74"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> or membranes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMilikSkolnick1993_75-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_meth=
od#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMilikSkolnick1993-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or <i>ab initio</i> framew=
orks depending on the desired accuracy.
Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particu=
lar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biomolecule" title=3D"Biomolec=
ule">molecule</a> to see if some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hemical_reaction" title=3D"Chemical reaction">chemical reaction</a> is happ=
ening for instance. In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical=
 experiment, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thought_experiment" t=
itle=3D"Thought experiment">thought experiments</a> can be conducted (for i=
nstance: breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing=
 the local/global structure, or introducing external fields).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computer_graphics">Computer=
 graphics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMo=
nte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Computer graphics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Path_tracing" title=3D"Path tra=
cing">Path tracing</a>, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing=
, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths. R=
epeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of th=
e samples to converge on the correct solution of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Rendering_equation" title=3D"Rendering equation">renderi=
ng equation</a>, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics =
rendering methods in existence.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Applied_statistics">Applied=
 statistics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Monte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Applied statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawi=
lowsky.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In applied st=
atistics, Monte Carlo methods may be used for at least four purposes:
</p>
<ol><li>To compare competing statistics for small samples under realistic d=
ata conditions. Although <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_er=
ror" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type I error">type I error</a> and powe=
r properties of statistics can be calculated for data drawn from classical =
theoretical distributions (<i>e.g.</i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Normal_curve" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Normal curve">normal cur=
ve</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_distribution" title=
=3D"Cauchy distribution">Cauchy distribution</a>) for <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymptotic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Asymptotic">=
asymptotic</a> conditions (<i>i. e</i>, infinite sample size and infinitesi=
mally small treatment effect), real data often do not have such distributio=
ns.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>To provide implementations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical =
hypothesis testing">hypothesis tests</a> that are more efficient than exact=
 tests such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_tests" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Permutation tests">permutation tests</a> (wh=
ich are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critica=
l values for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymptotic_distributi=
on" title=3D"Asymptotic distribution">asymptotic distributions</a>.</li>
<li>To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"Bayesian inf=
erence">Bayesian inference</a>. This sample then approximates and summarize=
s all the essential features of the posterior.</li>
<li>To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the nega=
tive log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher_information" title=3D"Fis=
her information">Fisher information</a> matrix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method=
#cite_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-79"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li></ol>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomizat=
ion and permutation tests. An approximate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Randomization_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Randomization te=
st">randomization test</a> is based on a specified subset of all permutatio=
ns (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations h=
ave been considered). The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified numb=
er of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if =
a permutation is drawn twice=E2=80=94or more frequently=E2=80=94for the eff=
iciency of not having to track which permutations have already been selecte=
d).
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Monte_Carlo_tree_search"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Artificial_intelligence_for=
_games">Artificial intelligence for games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Artificial intelligence for games"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_tree_sea=
rch" title=3D"Monte Carlo tree search">Monte Carlo tree search</a></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte-Carlo_tree_search" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Monte-Carlo tree search">Monte-Carlo tree search</a> that is=
 useful for searching for the best move in a game. Possible moves are organ=
ized in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_tree" title=3D"Se=
arch tree">search tree</a> and many random simulations are used to estimate=
 the long-term potential of each move. A black box simulator represents the=
 opponent's moves.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-80"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Monte Carlo tree search (MCTS) method has four steps:<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
onte_Carlo_method#cite_note-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ol><li>Starting at root node of the tree, select optimal child nodes until=
 a leaf node is reached.</li>
<li>Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.</li>
<li>Play a simulated game starting with that node.</li>
<li>Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ances=
tors.</li></ol>
<p>The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the val=
ue of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully correspondin=
g to whether or not that node represents a good move.
</p><p>Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games suc=
h as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(game)" title=3D"Go (game)=
">Go</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tantrix" title=3D"Tantrix">Tantrix</a>,<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Battleship_(game)" title=3D"Battleship (game)">Battleship</a=
>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Havannah_(board_game)" title=3D"Havannah (board game=
)">Havannah</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-85"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arimaa" title=3D"Arimaa">Arimaa</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_Go" title=3D"Co=
mputer Go">Computer Go</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Design_and_visuals">Design =
and visuals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Monte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Design and visuals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo methods are also efficient in solving coupled integral diffe=
rential equations of radiation fields and energy transport, and thus these =
methods have been used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_i=
llumination" title=3D"Global illumination">global illumination</a> computat=
ions that produce photo-realistic images of virtual 3D models, with applica=
tions in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game" title=3D"Vide=
o game">video games</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architect=
ure" title=3D"Architecture">architecture</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Design" title=3D"Design">design</a>, computer generated <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Film" title=3D"Film">films</a>, and cinem=
atic special effects.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESzirmay-Kalos2008_87-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_meth=
od#cite_note-FOOTNOTESzirmay-Kalos2008-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Search_and_rescue">Search a=
nd rescue</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMo=
nte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Search and rescue"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_Coast_Guard" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"US Coast Guard">US Coast Guard</a> utilizes Monte Carlo=
 methods within its computer modeling software <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/SAROPS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SAROPS">SAROPS</a> in o=
rder to calculate the probable locations of vessels during <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_and_rescue" title=3D"Search and rescue">sea=
rch and rescue</a> operations. Each simulation can generate as many as ten =
thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided vari=
ables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Search pattern=
s are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to op=
timize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detectio=
n (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).=
 Ultimately this serves as a practical application of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribu=
tion">probability distribution</a> in order to provide the swiftest and mos=
t expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-89" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mon=
te_Carlo_method#cite_note-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Finance_and_business">Finan=
ce and business</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Finance and business"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_methods_in_f=
inance" title=3D"Monte Carlo methods in finance">Monte Carlo methods in fin=
ance</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-Monte_Carlo_method=
s_in_finance" title=3D"Quasi-Monte Carlo methods in finance">Quasi-Monte Ca=
rlo methods in finance</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_=
Carlo_methods_for_option_pricing" title=3D"Monte Carlo methods for option p=
ricing">Monte Carlo methods for option pricing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_modelling_(insurance)" title=3D"Stochastic mod=
elling (insurance)">Stochastic modelling (insurance)</a>, and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_asset_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Stochastic asset model">Stochastic asset model</a></div>
<p>Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncerta=
inty that would affect the outcome of different decision options. Monte Car=
lo simulation allows the business risk analyst to incorporate the total eff=
ects of uncertainty in variables like sales volume, commodity and labor pri=
ces, interest and exchange rates, as well as the effect of distinct risk ev=
ents like the cancellation of a contract or the change of a tax law.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_methods_in_fina=
nce" title=3D"Monte Carlo methods in finance">Monte Carlo methods in financ=
e</a> are often used to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corporate_=
finance#Quantifying_uncertainty" title=3D"Corporate finance">evaluate inves=
tments in projects</a> at a business unit or corporate level, or other fina=
ncial valuations. They can be used to model <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Project_management" title=3D"Project management">project schedule=
s</a>, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and=
 most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall =
project.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-90" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-90"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Monte Carlo =
methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
nte_Carlo_method#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-kr11_92-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_meth=
od#cite_note-kr11-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Additionally, they can be used to estimat=
e the financial impact of medical interventions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_metho=
d#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Law">Law</h3><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Law"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a =
proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in t=
heir applications for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harassment_R=
estraining_Order" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Harassment Restraining Ord=
er">harassment</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domestic_Ab=
use_Restraining_Order" title=3D"Domestic Abuse Restraining Order">domestic =
abuse restraining orders</a>. It was proposed to help women succeed in thei=
r petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially red=
ucing the risk of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rape" title=3D"R=
ape">rape</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_assault=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Physical assault">physical assault</a>. Ho=
wever, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfec=
tly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of=
 petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others. The study ran=
 trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of =
the success level of the proposed program as a whole.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mo=
ntecarloanalysis_94-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-montecarloanalysis-94"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Library_science">Library sc=
ience</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_=
Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Lib=
rary science"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book p=
ublications based on book <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literary=
_genre" title=3D"Literary genre">genre</a> in Malaysia. The Monte Carlo sim=
ulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book=
's price according to book genre in the local market. The Monte Carlo resul=
ts were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond =
of and was used to compare book publications between <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Malaysia" title=3D"Malaysia">Malaysia</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan" title=3D"Japan">Japan</a>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-95" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
onte_Carlo_method#cite_note-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other">Other</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Other"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassim_Nicholas_Taleb" title=3D=
"Nassim Nicholas Taleb">Nassim Nicholas Taleb</a> writes about Monte Carlo =
generators in his 2001 book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foo=
led_by_Randomness" title=3D"Fooled by Randomness">Fooled by Randomness</a><=
/i> as a real instance of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reve=
rse_Turing_test" title=3D"Reverse Turing test">reverse Turing test</a>: a h=
uman can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart fr=
om a generated one.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use_in_mathematics">Use in =
mathematics</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Monte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Use in mathematics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve var=
ious problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_number_generation" title=3D"Random numbe=
r generation">Random number generation</a>) and observing that fraction of =
the numbers that obeys some property or properties. The method is useful fo=
r obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analyt=
ically. The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carl=
o integration.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integration">Integration</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_me=
thod&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Integration=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_integrat=
ion" title=3D"Monte Carlo integration">Monte Carlo integration</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Monte-carlo2.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Mo=
nte-carlo2.gif/250px-Monte-carlo2.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"246" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"401" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"395"></a><figcaption>Monte-Carlo integration works by comparing rand=
om points with the value of the function.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Monte-Carlo_method_(errors).png" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/8/89/Monte-Carlo_method_%28errors%29.png/250px-Monte-Carlo_method_%=
28errors%29.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"205" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"874" data-file-height=3D"717"></a><figca=
ption>Errors reduce by a factor of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math=
-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y=
" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM=
L" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"1">
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>/</mo>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <msqrt>
              <mi>N</mi>
            </msqrt>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \scriptstyle =
1/{\sqrt {N}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b0ed8ecb5f36fc5a2afacdde925d088e50ef38a3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:4.472ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \sc=
riptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}}"></span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Deterministic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_integra=
tion" title=3D"Numerical integration">numerical integration</a> algorithms =
work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when =
the functions have many variables. First, the number of function evaluation=
s needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions. For example, if 1=
0 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Googol" title=3D"Googol">10<sup>100</sup></a> =
points are needed for 100 dimensions=E2=80=94far too many to be computed. T=
his is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curse_of_dimensi=
onality" title=3D"Curse of dimensionality">curse of dimensionality</a>. Sec=
ond, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so =
it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Iterated_integral" title=3D"Iterated integral">iterated in=
tegral</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Press_96-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-Press-96"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> 100 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension" title=3D"Dimen=
sion">dimensions</a> is by no means unusual, since in many physical problem=
s, a "dimension" is equivalent to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Degrees_of_freedom_(physics_and_chemistry)" title=3D"Degrees of freedom (=
physics and chemistry)">degree of freedom</a>.
</p><p>Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase i=
n computation time. As long as the function in question is reasonably <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Well-behaved" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Well-behaved">well-behaved</a>, it can be estimated by randomly selec=
ting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of th=
e function values at these points. By the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Central limit theorem">central limi=
t theorem</a>, this method displays <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"1">
          <mn>1</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>/</mo>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <msqrt>
              <mi>N</mi>
            </msqrt>
          </mrow>
        </mstyle>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \scriptstyle =
1/{\sqrt {N}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b0ed8ecb5f36fc5a2afacdde925d088e50ef38a3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:4.472ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \sc=
riptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}}"></span> convergence=E2=80=94i.e., quadrupling the=
 number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dim=
ensions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Press_96-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-Press-96"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>A refinement of this method, known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Importance_sampling" title=3D"Importance sampling">importance sa=
mpling</a> in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more f=
requently where the integrand is large. To do this precisely one would have=
 to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an i=
ntegral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stratified_sampling" title=3D"Stratified sampl=
ing">stratified sampling</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mont=
e_Carlo_integration#Recursive_stratified_sampling" title=3D"Monte Carlo int=
egration">recursive stratified sampling</a>, adaptive umbrella sampling<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-97" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-98" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_met=
hod#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/VEGAS_algorithm" title=3D"VEGAS algorithm">VEGAS algorithm</a>.
</p><p>A similar approach, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qua=
si-Monte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Quasi-Monte Carlo method">quasi-Monte Carlo=
 method</a>, uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-discrepancy_=
sequence" title=3D"Low-discrepancy sequence">low-discrepancy sequences</a>.=
 These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important point=
s more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the i=
ntegral more quickly.
</p><p>Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simul=
ate random walks over it (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_c=
hain_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Markov chain Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Car=
lo</a>). Such methods include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Metropolis%E2%80%93Hastings_algorithm" title=3D"Metropolis=E2=80=93Hastings=
 algorithm">Metropolis=E2=80=93Hastings algorithm</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibbs_sampling" title=3D"Gibbs sampling">Gibbs samplin=
g</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wang_and_Landau_algorithm" =
title=3D"Wang and Landau algorithm">Wang and Landau algorithm</a>, and inte=
racting type MCMC methodologies such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Particle_filter" title=3D"Particle filter">sequential Monte Carlo=
</a> samplers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-99" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-99"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Simulation_and_optimization=
">Simulation and optimization</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Simulation and optimization"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_optimizat=
ion" title=3D"Stochastic optimization">Stochastic optimization</a></div>
<p>Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in nume=
rical simulation is in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimizatio=
n_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimization (mathematics)"=
>numerical optimization</a>. The problem is to minimize (or maximize) funct=
ions of some vector that often has many dimensions. Many problems can be ph=
rased in this way: for example, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Computer_chess" title=3D"Computer chess">computer chess</a> program could b=
e seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best e=
valuation function at the end. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Traveling_salesman_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Traveling sa=
lesman problem">traveling salesman problem</a> the goal is to minimize dist=
ance traveled. There are also applications to engineering design, such as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multidisciplinary_design_optimizati=
on" title=3D"Multidisciplinary design optimization">multidisciplinary desig=
n optimization</a>. It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models t=
o solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configura=
tion space. Reference<sup id=3D"cite_ref-100" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-100"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and op=
timization.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traveling_salesman_prob=
lem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Traveling salesman problem">traveling s=
alesman problem</a> is what is called a conventional optimization problem. =
That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to=
 determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal=
 is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with=
 the lowest total distance. If instead of the goal being to minimize the to=
tal distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minim=
ize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conve=
ntional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jam=
s, time of day, etc.). As a result, to determine the optimal path a differe=
nt simulation is required: optimization to first understand the range of po=
tential times it could take to go from one point to another (represented by=
 a probability distribution in this case rather than a specific distance) a=
nd then optimize the travel decisions to identify the best path to follow t=
aking that uncertainty into account.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inverse_problems">Inverse p=
roblems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMont=
e_Carlo_method&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: I=
nverse problems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>Probabilistic formulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
verse_problem" title=3D"Inverse problem">inverse problems</a> leads to the =
definition of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distri=
bution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a> in =
the model space. This probability distribution combines <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_probability" title=3D"Prior probability">prior<=
/a> information with new information obtained by measuring some observable =
parameters (data).
As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is n=
onlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to d=
escribe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
</p><p>When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood mo=
del is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution po=
wer of the data is desired. In the general case many parameters are modeled=
, and an inspection of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margina=
l_probability" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Marginal probability">margina=
l probability</a> densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless=
. But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of model=
s according to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_proba=
bility_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Posterior probability d=
istribution">posterior probability distribution</a> and to analyze and disp=
lay the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods o=
f model properties is conveyed to the spectator. This can be accomplished b=
y means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit=
 formula for the <i>a priori</i> distribution is available.
</p><p>The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm,=
 can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possi=
bly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex <i>a priori</i> informa=
tion and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_m=
ethod#cite_note-101"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-102" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-10=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Philosophy">Philosophy</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMonte_Carlo_meth=
od&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Philosophy"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The method's gene=
ral philosophy was discussed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El=
ishakoff" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elishakoff">Elishakoff</a><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-104" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and Gr=C3=BCne-Yanoff an=
d Weirich.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-105" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method#cite_note-105"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>105<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
